[1] Worldwide - 2011 data as of 5 Jan 2011
Date: 5 Jan 2012
Source: Polio eradication initiative website
http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek.aspx


2011 case count as of 5 Jan 2012:
Total cases: Year-to-date 2011 / Year-to-date 2010 / Total in 2010*
Globally: 620 / 920 / 1352
- endemic countries: 315 / 223 / 232
- non-endemic countries: 305 / 697 / 1120

The above represents data in WHO as of 4 Jan 2011 for 2010 data and 3 Jan 2012 for 2011 data.
*The 2010 total for Congo includes cases with inadequate specimens that have been exceptionally classified as confirmed polio based on their association with the WPV1 outbreak.


Afghanistan
Three new cases, all WPV1, were reported in the past week, bringing the total number of cases for 2011 to 74. The most recent case had onset of paralysis on [12 Dec 2011] in Maywand district in Kandahar province.

India
In the coming week, India will pass 12 months since the onset of paralysis of its most recent case. The case, which is the only case reported in India in 2011, had onset of paralysis on [13 Jan 2011] in West Bengal.

Nigeria
One new case was reported this week - the total number of cases for 2011 is now 51. The most recent case is a WPV1 with onset of paralysis on [27 Nov 2011] in Niger state.

Pakistan
Eight new cases were reported this week. The total number of cases in Pakistan is now 189. The most recent case (WPV1) had onset of paralysis on [16 Dec 2011], in Khyber, Federally Administered Tribal Areas.

Lot Quality Assurance Sampling methodology applied to the December [2011] Sub-national immunization days indicate that coverage was likely to be less than 80 percent in key transmission areas, such as northern Balochistan, and less than 90 percent in parts of southern Sindh. Of the 61 Union Councils surveyed, however, 39 were found likely to have coverage not less than 95 percent.

Angola
No new cases were reported in the past week. The country has reported a total of 5 cases in 2011, the most recent of which had onset of paralysis on 7 July in Uige in the country's north.

Chad and CAR
No new cases were reported in Chad this week, and the total number of cases is 130 (127 WPV1s and three WPV3s). The most recent case had onset of paralysis on [18 Nov 2011] (WPV1 from Logone Oriental).

One new case was reported from the Central African Republic (CAR) in the past week - the total number of cases for 2011 is now 4 (all WPV1s). CAR's most recent case had onset of paralysis on [8 Dec 2011] in Region Sanitaire 3 (RS3), in the country's north.

China
No new cases were reported in the past week. China has a total of 21 cases, all WPV1. The most recent had onset of paralysis on [9 Oct 2011] from Akesu prefecture.
China is at continued risk of circulation of wild poliovirus.

Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)
Three new cases were reported in the past week, bringing the total number of cases for 2011 to 92 (all WPV1). The most recent case had onset of paralysis on [28 Nov 2011] in Maniema province.

Horn of Africa
A case of WPV1 with onset of paralysis on [30 Jul 2011] in Nyanza province, western Kenya, remains the only case to be reported in the Horn of Africa in 2011.

West Africa
No new cases were reported in this region in the last week. The most recent case in west Africa is from Niger, with onset of paralysis on [17 Nov 2011] in Tahoua district, Birni Nkonni province, near the border with Nigeria. The total number of cases for 2011 in the west African region is 50 (36 from Cote d'Ivoire, 3 from Guinea, 7 from Mali and 4 from Niger). All cases are WPV3, except for 2 WPV1 cases from Niger.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Because of time lags associated with collection and testing of laboratory specimens submitted for confirmation of wild poliovirus (WPV infection), and in some cases, delays in identifying suspected cases in areas with reduced access to health services, one expects to continue to have reports of cases of WPV associated disease from 2011 during the early weeks of 2012. The above information includes information from the official report of the status of 2011 WPV associated disease as of Thurs. 5 Jan 2012.

A map of the geographic locations of WPV confirmed cases in 2011 can be found at: http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring.aspx. Looking at the map one can see a band of "heavy" transmission in Asia, most notably in Pakistan and Afghanistan with the spill over (via importation followed by local transmission) into western China. There are also bands of WPV1 transmission in Chad, the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Nigeria, and bands of WPV3 transmission in Cote d'Ivoire and Nigeria.

While it is very noteworthy that India is on the verge of completing a full year without reports of WPV associated disease (the most recent date of onset was 13 Jan 2011 in West Bengal), the continued transmission of WPV in neighboring Pakistan is a reminder of the continued risk of re-introduction of WPV.

The findings of the Lot Quality Assessment performed in Pakistan following the last rounds of immunization activities in December 2011 are disheartening, as vaccination coverages in known areas of WPV transmission are suboptimal (less than 80 percent), translating into continued pockets of inadequate vaccination coverages where WPV will most likely continue to circulate. - Mod.MPP]

